Yes, both are known MSTest v4 behavioral changes. Here's what's happening:

**1. Tests appear as new in Azure DevOps** — The `TestCase.Id` generation algorithm changed in v4 to fix bugs. This breaks history continuity. There's no code fix; results will re-baseline automatically going forward.

**2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`** — v4 now enforces lifecycle scoping. `TestName` is per-test context and isn't available during class-level init. Move that access to `[TestInitialize]` or individual test methods.

**Other things to watch out for:**

| Change | Impact |
|---|---|
| `TreatDiscoveryWarningsAsErrors` now defaults to **true** | Tests with discovery warnings will fail entirely instead of running |
| `DisableAppDomain` defaults to **true** | May cause hangs on .NET Framework if your tests relied on AppDomain isolation |
| MSTest.Sdk defaults to MTP mode | `vstest.console` won't find tests — switch CI to `dotnet test` or set `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` |
| Several analyzers upgraded to Warning | MSTEST0001, 0007, 0017, 0023–0025, 0030–0032, 0035, 0037, 0045 may produce new warnings |

For the `TestContext` issue specifically, the fix looks like:

```csharp
// ❌ Throws in v4
[ClassInitialize]
public static void ClassInit(TestContext ctx)
{
    var name = ctx.TestName; // throws
}

// ✅ Move to TestInitialize
[TestInitialize]
public void TestInit()
{
    var name = TestContext.TestName; // works here
}
```

